      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That yellowing at the bottom of your tomato stems is likely a classic sign of nutrient deficiency or water stress, often caused by the plant using up its reserves as it grows taller. To fix the soil, you should test its pH and add a balanced organic fertilizer or compost to replenish the missing nutrients. It's also important to ensure your watering schedule is consistent, as both overwatering and underwatering can cause those lower leaves to yellow while the top remains green. If you're seeing any signs of pests like spider mites or aphids, you might want to inspect the undersides of the leaves for tiny insects or webbing. Treating the soil with a slow-release fertilizer and maintaining proper moisture levels should help your plants recover and produce more fruit.",
