      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm thinking it might be nitrogen since you mentioned it. how do i actually check the ph and what should i add to the dirt to bring it back to level? i don't want to mess up the balance too much or i'll ruin the whole crop.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can check your soil pH using a simple digital meter or a test kit, which is much more accurate than guessing. If the soil is too acidic, you can add lime to raise the pH, but if it's too alkaline, adding sulfur or peat moss will help bring it back to the ideal range of 6.0 to 6.8 for tomatoes. To avoid ruining your crop, always apply amendments in small amounts and mix them thoroughly into the soil before watering, as a sudden shift can shock the roots. If you're unsure, it's best to start with a gentle application of compost, which naturally balances pH without being too aggressive. Just remember that adding too much fertilizer too quickly can actually burn your plants, so a slow, steady approach is key.",
