      "content": "It sounds like your soil might be leaching nutrients rapidly, which is common in sandy soils or if you're using too much water without enough organic matter to hold the nutrients. Another possibility is that your plants are simply outgrowing their existing nutrient reserves, which is normal as they mature, or you might be using a fertilizer that isn't compatible with your specific soil type. To prevent this, try adding more compost or well-rotted manure to improve soil structure and water retention, which will help the nutrients stay available to your plants longer. Additionally, ensure you aren't over-fertilizing with a quick-release fertilizer that can wash away before the plants can absorb it. If the problem persists, consider doing a soil test to identify exactly what's missing and adjust your feeding schedule accordingly.",
